Aim:

Simulation of Airline Passenger Processing System

Theory:

An airline passenger processing system manages passengers through different stages such 
as check-in, security screening, and boarding. Passengers arrive at the airport, wait in
queues if service counters are busy, and proceed sequentially through each stage before boarding.

This simulation models the passenger flow through:

Check-in counters
Security checkpoints
Boarding process

The system helps analyze:

Queue length
Waiting time
Resource utilization
Passenger flow efficiency
COMMANDS:
GENERATE
Creates passenger arrivals at specified intervals.
QUEUE
Places passengers into waiting lines.
SEIZE
Allocates a service facility to a passenger.
DEPART
Removes passengers from the queue after service begins.
ADVANCE
Simulates processing time.
RELEASE
Frees the facility after service completion.
TERMINATE
Removes the passenger from the system or stops the simulation.
EQU
Defines facility identifiers.
Scenario Overview:

The airline passenger processing system contains:

One check-in counter
One security checkpoint
Sequential passenger movement

Passengers arrive every 5 minutes and proceed through:

Check-in
Security screening
Boarding gate access

If the facilities are busy, passengers wait in queues until service becomes available.

Key Components:
1. Passengers

Passengers arrive randomly and move through all airport processing stages.

2. Check-In Counter

Handles ticket verification and baggage processing.

3. Security Checkpoint

Performs passenger security screening.

4. Queues

Separate queues are maintained for:

Check-in
Security
5. Boarding Process

Passengers proceed to boarding after completing all checks.

Small Conclusion Template

The GPSS simulation represents an airline passenger processing system with check-in and
security stages. Passengers were processed sequentially through each stage with queue management 
and service facilities. The simulation helps evaluate passenger flow, waiting time, and resource 
utilization for efficient airport operations.
